  "texts": [
    "Customers' expectations of accident losses depend on their knowledge of risk (Shavell, 2004, 213).",
    "When product risk is perfectly observable to consumers, they factor in accident costs when deciding to buy, considering both the product's market price and expected accident losses (Shavell, 2004, 207).",
    "Expected harm directly influences the price, reducing the demand for risky products regardless of the liability rule on producers-no liability, negligence, or strict liability (Shavell, 2004, 212).",
    "14 As riskier products will have a higher perceived price, competition will compel producers to take optimal care to avoid sales drops (Polinsky & 1 3",
    "European Journal of Law and Economics (2024) 57:239-273 Shavell, 2010, 1441)."
